1. Objective
To build a binary classification model that accurately predicts if a person's income exceeds $50K/yr (Class >50K) or falls below it (Class <=50K) based on features like age, education, occupation, and working hours.

2. Dataset Details
We will use the Adult Data Set from the UCI Machine Learning Repository.

Instances: ~32,561 (Training)

Features: 14 attributes (Categorical and Numerical)

Target Variable: income (>50K or <=50K)

Key Features Include:

age: Continuous integer.

workclass: Private, State-gov, Federal-gov, Self-emp, etc.

education: Bachelors, Some-college, 11th, HS-grad, etc.

marital-status: Married, Divorced, Never-married, etc.

occupation: Tech-support, Craft-repair, Exec-managerial, etc.

hours-per-week: Continuous integer representing work hours.

3. Methodology
Data Loading: Fetch the data directly from the UCI repository using Pandas.

Data Cleaning: The dataset contains missing values represented by " ?". We will replace these with NaN and drop those rows to keep the dataset clean.

Feature Encoding:

Machine learning models require numerical input. We will use LabelEncoder to convert categorical text data (like occupation or education) into numeric labels.

We will also encode the target variable (income) into 0 and 1.

Feature Scaling: We will use StandardScaler to normalize numerical features (like capital-gain or age) so that larger numbers don't disproportionately dominate the model.

Model Training: We will use a Random Forest Classifier, which is highly effective for datasets with a mix of categorical and numerical data.

Evaluation: We will assess the model using Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and the F1-Score.
